=== Press Release ===
Title: 232 Persons Caught for E-Vaporiser Offences, 14 Confirmed to Possess Etomidate Vapes, in First Week of Enhanced Penalties
Date: 2025-09-08
Source: Ministry of Health (MOH) / Health Sciences Authority (HSA)
Document Type: Press Release
Topic: Vaping, Etomidate, Enforcement, Rehabilitation, Public Support

Summary:
- Following enhanced penalties for vaping offences from 1 September 2025, 232 individuals were caught for e-vaporiser offences; 14 confirmed to possess etomidate-laced vapes.
- Notices of Composition issued; suspected etomidate abusers required to attend rehabilitation.
- First etomidate e-vaporiser trafficker charged under Misuse of Drugs Act (MDA): Khor Boon Chun, Derek.
- Government mobilises over 5,000 frontline officers across agencies to enforce anti-vaping measures.
- Public plays key role in reporting illegal activities and safe disposal of e-vaporisers (“Bin the Vape” initiative).
- Voluntary support programmes: QuitVape, HPB I Quit programme, IMH and SSAs for etomidate vaping cessation.
- Enhanced penalties: escalating fines and rehabilitation requirements for repeated offenders; severe penalties for importers, sellers, and distributors of etomidate e-vaporisers.

Key Entities:
- Ministry of Health (MOH)
- Health Sciences Authority (HSA)
- Central Narcotics Bureau (CNB)
- Corrupt Practices Investigation Bureau (CPIB)
- Land Transport Authority (LTA)
- Ministry of Manpower (MOM)
- Singapore Civil Defence Force (SCDF)
- Singapore Prison Service
- Singapore Police Force
- Immigration & Checkpoints Authority (ICA)
- Ministry of Education (MOE)
- National Environment Agency (NEA)
- National Parks Board (NParks)
- Khor Boon Chun, Derek (trafficker)
- Social Service Agencies (SSAs): SANA, WeCare, THKMC, Fei Yue
- Health Promotion Board (HPB)
- Institutes of Mental Health (IMH)

Key Concepts:
- Enhanced enforcement for vaping offences
- Etomidate-laced e-vaporisers
- Notices of Composition (NOC)
- Rehabilitation programmes (3–6 months)
- Voluntary cessation programmes: QuitVape, I Quit
- Community support and vigilance
- Bin the Vape initiative
- Escalating penalties for repeat offenders
- Importers, sellers, distributors penalties (imprisonment and caning)
- Public reporting channels

Body:
1. Following the enhanced penalties on 1 September 2025, 232 individuals were caught for e-vaporiser offences; 14 confirmed to possess etomidate-laced vapes.
2. 32 suspected etomidate abusers; 14 confirmed, 7 negative, 11 pending test results.
3. Rehabilitation required for confirmed etomidate abusers, up to six months, with education, counselling, and support.
4. Over 5,000 frontline officers authorised to enforce against e-vaporiser offences, doubling the previous enforcement force.
5. First etomidate e-vaporiser trafficker charged under MDA: Khor Boon Chun, Derek; seized pods tested positive for etomidate.
6. Public vigilance highlighted as critical in detecting illegal activities.
7. Support available for voluntary quitters via QuitVape, HPB I Quit programme, IMH, and participating SSAs; no penalties for voluntary participation.
8. “Bin the Vape” initiative: ~6,000 e-vaporisers voluntarily disposed from 25 July – 31 Aug 2025; continued safe disposal at selected locations.
9. Enhanced penalties: higher fines and rehabilitation for repeated users; prosecution for third-time offenders under TCASA.
10. Etomidate offenders: second-time – investigation, urine testing, mandatory supervision; third-time (16+ years) – 12-month regime including Drug Rehabilitation Centre (DRC), drug testing, supervision.
11. Importers, sellers, distributors of etomidate e-vaporisers face 3–20 years’ imprisonment + 5–15 strokes of the cane (importers) or 2–10 years + 2–5 strokes (sellers/distributors).
12. Public reporting channels: online form (www.go.gov.sg/reportvape), QR code, or call Tobacco Regulation Branch (6684 2036 / 6684 2037), 9am–9pm daily.
13. Reinforcement of Singapore’s ban on vaping and commitment to supporting cessation efforts.

Author / Issuer:
Ministry of Health (MOH)
Health Sciences Authority (HSA)
Date of Issue: 2025-09-08
